The Black fire was reported by a retired FS employee.  E604 responded and suppressed the fire.
The Coal Mountain fire was reported by a resident, and E663 responded and suppressed the fire.
The Roaring Judy fire was a human caused fire that had smoldered some time before detection.  Jerry Chonka and Art Haines responded and suppressed the fire.
The Cow Creek fire was reported by a resident in the White Pine area.  IC Jerry Chonka responded with a squad of firefighters from the Gunnison office and suppressed the fire with direct attack.
The Sims Mesa fire was reported by Jeff Gehlhausen while collecting fuel samples.  Engine 663 with IC Gehlhausen responded and suppressed the fire with direct attack.
The Craig Draw fire was reported by a resident.  Engine 438 with IC Duensing responded and suppressed the fire with direct attack.

The Crested Butte Mtn. fire was reported by Crested Butte VFD, on the ski hill.  They responded, and requested USFS assistance as it was on FS lands.  IC Spetter with E671 and 5 firefighters suppressed the fire with direct attack.

The One Mile fire was reported by a resident as visible from the Elsinor Ranch.  IC Brian Stevens, Jerry Chonka, and E671 responded and suppressed the fire.  Local residents had previously worked the fire.
The Glenco fire was reported by a local resident.  IC Luke Odom, with ICT4-T Joe Duensing responded with E438, E663, E651, and the IA Squad and suppressed the fire with direct attack.
The Iron Springs fire was reported by USFS LEO Dave Claussen.  IC Tanner Hutt with E651, Chase 651, and the IA Squad responded and suppressed the fire with direct attack.
The Ditch fire was reported in the Thunder Road area by a private citizen.  Engine 651 responded with IC Tanner Hutt, and suppressed the fire with direct attack.
The Slide 2 fire was discovered by Tanner Hutt when responding to the Slide fire.  This fire was also deemed to be surrounded by scree, and was monitored until declared out.

Fire burned entirely within the West Elk Wilderness area.  Poor access and difficult terrain (cliffs, rock, steep slopes) and concern for firefighter safety were the primary reasons for selectiong confinement strategy.  Duration 153 days.

The Albin Draw WFU was located across the San Miguel River Canyon. IC Tanner Hutt responded, and then Luke Odom transitioned to IC.  The fire burned in roller chop units for a week, making several runs until the summer rains put it out.

The Beaver fire was reported by a Sheriff's Deputy.  Engine 431 with IC Trainee Ricky Colton responded and suppressed the fire.  The fire was of unknown origin, with ATV tracks nearby, possibly caused by exhaust.
